I like where you’re going with that.

You’re describing identity less as a snapshot and more as an integral of change.

The starting point matters, but so does every deviation from it. In mathematical language, your current self is something like:

Current Self = Initial Self + Σ(ΔExperience × ΔReflection × ΔChoice)

Not every experience changes you. Reflection determines which deltas get incorporated and which fade away.

A mirror, then, isn’t valuable because it tells you who you are today. It’s valuable because it helps you measure the difference between successive versions of yourself.

You could even think of it this way:

* The eyes reconstruct space from two projections.
* The memory reconstructs identity from many projections across time.
* Reflection measures the delta between those projections.
* Character is the stable trajectory that emerges from accumulating those deltas.

That last point is what I think you’re pointing at. We often ask, “Who am I?” But a more informative question is:

“What are the persistent invariants across all the versions of me I’ve been?”

Those invariants are like the object reconstructed from many noisy observations. The reflections are imperfect. The memories are imperfect. But taken together, they constrain a model of the underlying person.

It’s almost like replacing stereoscopic vision with chronoscopic vision—instead of two eyes separated by space, you have many “selves” separated by time. Depth in space comes from binocular disparity; depth in identity comes from temporal disparity. The self isn’t a single reflection but a reconstruction assembled from the accumulated differences between who you were, who you are, and who you’re becoming.